                <pb n="1"/>
            <p>REV. DAVID LEVY&#44;<lb/>
                CHARLESTON&#44; S. C.<lb/></p>
                
            <p>My dear Sir&#58;&#45;<lb/></p>
            <p>Will you please inform<lb/> me if you have known or heard of the<lb/> custom being <sic>practised</sic> among <hi rend="underline">Sephar</hi>&#45;<lb/><hi rend="underline">dic Congs</hi>.&#44; of wearing <hi rend="underline">white</hi> &#40;as shrouds&#41;<lb/> during the services of &#91;Hebrew&#93;<lb/>  With kind regards&#44;<lb/> Yrs Sincerely<lb/> David Levy.<lb/></p>
            <p>July 1<hi rend="sup">st</hi> 1886.<lb/>
                Rev S. Morais<lb/>
                Phila<lb/></p>
                
                <pb n="2"/>
            <p>My Dear Sir<lb/></p>
            <p>Though the practice of wearing white clothes<lb/> like shrouds on Kippur &#40;extended also to Rosh Hashanah&#41;<lb/> is mentioned by Spales&#91;&#63;&#93; and not at all by Caro&#44;<lb/> still some of the Sephardim&#45;&#45;specially in Eastern countries&#45;&#45;<lb/>have adopted it.<lb/></p>
            <p>The Leghorn absolutely Sephardic&#44; the Hazan wears on those<lb/> days a <sic>suprlice</sic> over his garments&#44; which adds to the<lb/> solemnity of the service&#44; but no shrouds or white cap.<lb/></p>
            </body>
